  <discussion>Celtis occidentalis is valued as an ornamental street tree because of its tolerance to drought.</discussion>
  <discussion>Native Americans used decoctions prepared from the bark of Celtis occidentalis medicinally as an aid in menses and to treat sore throat (D. E. Moerman 1986).</discussion>
  <discussion>This is a highly variable species. Segregates named as varieties follow an east-west geographic gradient and are based primarily on leaf size, shape, and pubescence.</discussion>
